#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""
engram-pkg — CLI toolkit for authoring engram-package databases.

Operates on any engram-package directory passed via --pkg or $ENGRAM_PKG.
Wraps the EngramClient (which redirects all server paths to the package
directory atomically) so you can author into the package without touching
your personal engram at ~/.engram/.

Usage:
    engram-pkg --pkg ~/engram-packages/wiki/ <subcommand> [args...]
    ENGRAM_PKG=~/engram-packages/wiki/ engram-pkg <subcommand> [args...]

Common subcommands:
    init               Bootstrap a new engram-package skeleton in an empty directory.
    add-evidence       Register a source document.
    add-observation    Extract a claim with provenance from a source.
    derive             Combine evidence into a derived claim.
    supersede          Replace an existing node with an updated version.
    list               List nodes in the package (compact triage).
    query              Search nodes by text + embedding.
    inspect            Inspect a single node + 1-hop neighbors.
    stats              Package statistics.
    dump               Run scripts/dump.sh — write knowledge.sql.
    build              Run scripts/build.sh — build knowledge.db from .sql.
    call               Generic escape hatch — invoke any engram_* tool by name with JSON args.
    scope-export       Export a provenance closure of cited nodes as a scoped engram-package.

Why a CLI rather than MCP-tool duplication: parallel personal vs package
MCP tools share shape and selection signal; mid-flow it's easy to fire the
wrong one. The conscious shell command makes the namespace shift visible
and matches the tool surface other agents (e.g., Mneme) will use.
"""

